Shebang refers to the line at the beginning of a Unix shell script that specifies the interpreter used to execute the script. Ancient Egypt was known as Kemet (or Black Land) because of the fertile black soil that existed along the Nile River. This soil was created by the annual flooding of the Nile, which deposited silt and nutrients on the land. The black soil was ideal for growing crops such as wheat, barley, and flax, which were essential to the Egyptian economy and way of life. The name Kemet reflects the importance of this land for agriculture and the Egyptian civilization that flourished there.

Yes, fever during early pregnancy can increase the risk of miscarriage. High body temperature can cause damage to the developing embryo and can also disrupt the implantation of the fertilized egg in the uterus. However, the risk of miscarriage due to fever is generally low, and most women who experience a fever in early pregnancy will not experience a miscarriage. A ALM (Application Lifecycle Management) is a set of tools and processes used to manage the development, testing, and deployment of software applications throughout their lifecycle. It includes all the activities involved in creating, maintaining, and retiring software applications, from initial planning to deployment and beyond. ALM typically includes version control, build automation, testing, and defect tracking, as well as collaboration and communication tools for developers, testers, and other stakeholders. The goal of ALM is to streamline the software development process, improve productivity, and reduce the risk of errors and defects.
